  "prompt": "How do you overwrite the output directory when using PySpark?",
  "response": "In PySpark, there are several ways to overwrite the output directory when saving data:\n\n1. Using `mode()` method:\n```python\n# Overwrite the entire output directory\ndf.write.mode(\"overwrite\").parquet(\"/path/to/output\")\n\n# Alternative modes:\n# - \"overwrite\": Overwrite existing data\n# - \"append\": Add new data\n# - \"ignore\": Skip if directory exists\n# - \"error\" (default): Throw an error if directory exists\n```\n\n2. Explicitly setting overwrite option:\n```python\ndf.write.format(\"parquet\") \\\n    .mode(\"overwrite\") \\\n    .save(\"/path/to/output\")\n```\n\n3. When using Spark SQL:\n```python\nspark.sql(\"SET spark.sql.sources.partitionOverwriteMode=dynamic\")\ndf.write.mode(\"overwrite\").partitionBy(\"column\").parquet(\"/path/to/output\")\n```\n\n4. For specific file formats:\n```python\n# CSV\ndf.write.mode(\"overwrite\").csv(\"/path/to/output\")\n\n# Parquet\ndf.write.mode(\"overwrite\").parquet(\"/path/to/output\")\n\n# JSON\ndf.write.mode(\"overwrite\").json(\"/path/to/output\")\n```\n\n5. Using `SaveMode` enum (less common):\n```python\nfrom pyspark.sql.utils import SaveMode\n\ndf.write.mode(SaveMode.Overwrite).parquet(\"/path/to/output\")\n```\n\nKey points to remember:\n- `mode(\"overwrite\")` will completely replace the existing directory\n- Ensure you have write permissions to the output directory\n- Be cautious as this will delete existing data in the specified path\n\nExample with more context:\n```python\nfrom pyspark.sql import SparkSession\n\n# Create Spark session\nspark = SparkSession.builder.appName(\"OverwriteExample\").getOrCreate()\n\n# Create a sample DataFrame\ndf = spark.createDataFrame([(1, \"Alice\"), (2, \"Bob\")], [\"id\", \"name\"])\n\n# Overwrite the output directory\ndf.write.mode(\"overwrite\").parquet(\"/tmp/output_data\")\n```\n\nThis approach works across different file systems, including local file system, HDFS, and cloud storage systems like S3.",
